result.execSummary:
The defendant Katherine Kimbrough was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery to Law Enforcement Officers, Fire Fighters or Commission Wardens, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.20(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Huber for work and treatment; good time allowed.

miscConds.notes: Pay the DNA surcharge, costs, disbursements and supervision fees. Failure to pay would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant which is non-dischargable in bankruptcy.

Job and vocational training.
Seek and maintain employment.
The Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon not to possess any firearms/body armor.

No alcohol.
No controlled substances other than those legally prescribed for defendant by duly licensed physician for her mental or physical needs.

Court ordered to provide a DNA sample.
Undergo a mental health evaluation; follow thru with any treatment recommended.
Urine screens.
Court recommended to Probation Department to refer defendant to Benedict Center; defendant must comply with all treatment and programming recommended.
Anger management.
Cognitive thinking intervention counseling.
Court further advised defendant of voting ineligibility.
